@ThinkingandTinkering I apologize for the "Disappointing" comment. I shouldn't have written that.  
Delivered, manufactured solar pv arrays have great quality issues in manufacture and design, and seldom output their nameplate capacity or last for a large portion of their rated life span.  PV panel output ratings and capacities are inflated, not altogether differently from the ratings for wind turbines you reviewed some time ago. Their output is also subject to reduction, losing capacity at about 1% per year -- this is especially so in high temperature conditions, but cold weather is also difficult.  The best open, freely available land is not close to where the people live or industries are located, rendering cost of delivery infrastructure too high and causing additional environmental damage.  There's more, but pv is far from a usable or practical technology, and all too likely to be used unwisely and too soon, despite recent availability and promotion.  
As a practical, deliverable, current replacement for fossil fuels, PV is very disappointing.

