@ThinkingandTinkering I just use car batteries. Yes, I think a variety is important for resilience. I try and avoid inverters but I do have three petrol generators (which I also avoid using). Although they can generate 110/240vAC I normally only use the 12vDC outputs. Petrol is just stored solar energy so I don't feel guilty.
Mostly I try to use 12vDC for everything electrical (i.e. from car parts). But I do have a gas absorption fridge - so quiet. And other propane kitchen items.
I reduced my energy usage simply by going completely off-grid. I live in the middle of a city so that was difficult. Especially as it's in a two up two down terrace with no garden. Gradually I put back items as needed. Some were successful, some not. Currently I'm examining rain water harvesting. I'm not sure this will be successful though as it has to compete with cheap bottled water from the supermarket.  I have two main aims. Make sure any visitors don't notice I am off grid (i.e. everything looks "normal"). Run a normal washing machine using off grid resources only.

@ThinkingandTinkering With all due respect because I’m not attacking you or your video I am just trying to rationalize the video title, the currently accepted value for global average direct solar irradiance before our atmosphere is roughly 1361 W/m2. At sea level, when the sun is directly above you and there are no clouds you will see about 1050W/m2. Maybe I misunderstood but I struggled to see how UK can see a peak 1.2-1.3kW/ m2 average irradiance on ground level.


The issue with using peak values for estimates is that you will only get peak values of solar irradiance during summer with the sun at its zenith and only for about an hour with a bell curve that is more dramatic at larger latitudes. That said 1kW/m2 is what we take as the peak where your 1 square meter panel will generate 200w for only about an hour before it begins to drop off. Even if your solar panel rotates to keep the peak efficiency angle for the panel, solar irradiance drops off steeply when away from the equator. So you cannot use amount of daylight hours to calculate average panel power without integrating the irradiance curve. People tend to use Average Peak Sun Hours for these calculations as an fair estimate. Grids only care about peak power generation for handling surge demand or meeting reactive power demand which is less important with solar because supply cannot be cannot be increased on the fly. 
I may be ignorant of grid sized energy storage abilities. Please enlighten me as to how we may be able to store enough energy to make of nightly deficits or handle demand peaks because as far as I know the cost and efficiency of these systems are still prohibitive despite some novel ideas.
